%N A246641 Sequence a(n) = (1 + A007805(n))/2, appearing in a certain touching problem for three circles and a chord, together with A007805.
%C A246641 This sequence is motivated by Kival Ngaokrajang's touching circle problem considered in A092387 and A115032.
%C A246641 a(n), together with b(n) = A007805(n), appears in a sequence of curvatures c(n) = 4*(b(n) + a(n)*phi), with phi = (1+sqrt(5))/2, the golden section, and n >= 0. These are integers in the real quadratic number field Q(sqrt(5)).
%C A246641 The circle with curvature c(n) touches i) the chord of length 2 (in some length units) bisecting a circular disk of radius 5/4, and ii) two touching circles in the larger section with curvatures given by c1(n) and c1(n+1), where c1(n) = A115032(n-1), with c1(0) = 1. See the illustration of Kival Ngaokrajang's link given in A092387, where the first circles in the larger (lower) section are shown.
%C A246641 From Descartes' theorem on touching circles (see the links), one has here: c(n) = c1(n) + c1(n+1) + 2*sqrt(c1(n)*c1(n+1)), with c1(n) = (1 + S(n, 18) - 9*S(n-1, 18))/2, n >= 0, where Chebyshev's S-polynomials (see A049310) appear. See also the W. Lang link in A092387, part I. In this application curvature 0 for the chord is used.
%C A246641 For the proof for the first a(n) formula given below use the above given curvature c1(n) in Descartes' formula and compare it with a(n) from c(n) = 4*(A007805(n) + a(n)* (1+sqrt(5))/2). This can be done by using standard S-polynomial identities like the three term recurrence for S(n+1, 18) and the Cassini-Simson type identity (see a comment on A246638) which implies the formula S(n, 18)*S(n-1, 18) = (-1 + S(n, 18)^2 + S(n-1, 18)^2)/18. See also the W. Lang link in A092387 part IV a).
